Get data from Twitter API...

In [4]:
%%script false

import tweepy
from tweepy import OAuthHandler
import json
from timeit import default_timer as timer
import credentials

# Query Twitter API for each tweet in the Twitter archive and save JSON in a text file
# These are hidden to comply with Twitter's API terms and conditions
consumer_key    = credentials.consumer_key
consumer_secret = credentials.consumer_secret
access_token    = credentials.access_token
access_secret   = credentials.access_secret

auth = OAuthHandler(consumer_key, consumer_secret)
auth.set_access_token(access_token, access_secret)

api = tweepy.API(auth, wait_on_rate_limit=True, wait_on_rate_limit_notify=True)

# NOTE TO STUDENT WITH MOBILE VERIFICATION ISSUES:
# df_1 is a DataFrame with the twitter_archive_enhanced.csv file. You may have to
# change line 17 to match the name of your DataFrame with twitter_archive_enhanced.csv
# NOTE TO REVIEWER: this student had mobile verification issues so the following
# Twitter API code was sent to this student from a Udacity instructor
# Tweet IDs for which to gather additional data via Twitter's API
tweet_ids = df_archive.tweet_id.values
print('Number of tweets =', len(tweet_ids))
print()

# Query Twitter's API for JSON data for each tweet ID in the Twitter archive
count = 0
success = 0
fail = 0
fails_dict = {}
start = timer()

# Save each tweet's returned JSON as a new line in a .txt file
with open('tweet_json.txt', 'w') as outfile:
    # This loop will likely take 20-30 minutes to run because of Twitter's rate limit
    print('Retriving tweets via Twitter API:\n')
    print('{:>5}{:>15}{:>15}{:>20}'.format('Count', 'Success', 'Fail', 'Time (min)'))

    for tweet_id in tweet_ids:
        count += 1
        try:
            tweet = api.get_status(tweet_id, tweet_mode='extended')
            success += 1
#            print(str(count) + ": " + str(tweet_id) + " - Success")
            json.dump(tweet._json, outfile)
            outfile.write('\n')
        except tweepy.TweepError as e:
            fail += 1
#            print(str(count) + ": " + str(tweet_id) + " - Fail")
            fails_dict[tweet_id] = e
            pass
        if count%100 == 0:
            print('{:>5}{:>15}{:>15}{:>20}'.format(count, success, fail, round((timer()-start)/60,2)))

end = timer()

print()
print('Retrieved tweets =', count, '/ Success =', success,
      '/ Fail =', fail, '/ Time =', round((end-start)/60,2), "minutes")

Quality issue (3):

Define: breed predictions should be combined in one column prioritizing from 1 to 3, then rows with tweets that are not dogs in all prediction columns should be dropped

Code:

In [26]:
breed = []

def dog_breed(df):
    if   df['p1_dog']: breed.append(df['p1'])
    elif df['p2_dog']: breed.append(df['p2'])
    elif df['p3_dog']: breed.append(df['p3'])
    else: breed.append(pd.np.nan)
    
df_final.apply(dog_breed, axis=1)

Q6: What observations can you make from tweets character length?¶

In [76]:
print('-'*40)

print('The  mode  of "tweet_length" =', round(df_final['tweet_length'].mode()[0],0))
print('-'*40)

plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 7))

plt.xlabel('Tweet Length', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Frequency', fontsize=12)

----------------------------------------
The  mean  of "tweet_length" = 112.0
The median of "tweet_length" = 116.0
The  mode  of "tweet_length" = 141
----------------------------------------

The mean character length of tweets in the dataset is 112 characters, while the median is 116. However, the mode represents the maximum characters allowed by Twitter at the time.

The graph below is the frequency of Tweets by character length (1 to 140 characters) from the 500 million Tweet samples used by Scott Golder and Vladimir Barash (sample extracted from Twitter in late 2009) in their academic papers*.

Notice the similarities between this graph and our calculated one above. Tweet lengths are almost stable up to around 130 characters, then a spike at the maximum limit.

*Source: Abductive Intelligence https://tmblr.co/ZrDhKyEYN7K6

Q7: How does dog stage rank when considered against the means and counts of retweets and likes?¶

In [78]:
plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 10))

When considering means of retweets we find doggo is the top stage followed by puppo stage. But when we look at means of likes the ranking is reversed where puppo is the top stage followed by doggo stage. This is followed by the rest of the stages at the same ranking.

However, when we consider the counts of retweets and likes, the top rank goes to the pupper stage by a wide margin, more than the other stages combined!

plt.grid(True, alpha=0.25)

It looks like the audience of We Rate Dogs account expanded over the time line of the dataset. The favorite and retweet count monthly mean increased in a linear fashion over time, while enjoying some viral moments (like Jun '16). Obviously, favorites far exceeded retweets.

Q11: What are the most represented years, months, and days across the time line of the dataset?¶

In [82]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 14))
plt.subplot(3, 1, 1)
df_final.groupby(df_final.timestamp.apply(lambda x:x.year))['tweet_id'].count().sort_values().plot(kind='barh')
plt.ylabel('Year')
plt.subplot(3, 1, 2)
df_final.groupby(df_final.timestamp.apply(lambda x:x.month_name()))['tweet_id'].count().sort_values().plot(kind='barh')
plt.ylabel('Month')
plt.subplot(3, 1, 3)
df_final.groupby(df_final.timestamp.apply(lambda x:x.day_name()))['tweet_id'].count().sort_values().plot(kind='barh')
plt.ylabel('Day')
plt.xlabel('Count');

The most represented year is 2016, this is probably because it is the only full year in the dataset. Followed by 2015, which as shown before was the start of the account and the initial tweetstorm.

The most represented months are December and November for reasons similar to the above as they occurred twice in the time line, once during the initial tweetstorm. August, on the other hand, is the least represented month because although it occurred twice, one was during a decline.

The most represented day is Monday, and the least represented is the weekend. It only makes sense that the owner of the account wanted to enjoy their weekend and save the heavy work to Monday.
